Don’t forget that, to make a prediction for the new city, you’ll need to unscale the coefficients (i.e., do the scaling calculation in reverse)!)

#using factoextra in R to help interpret the above PCA #the eigenvalues as mentioned in the lecture measure the amount of variation retained by each principal component.An eigenvalue > 1 indicates that PCs account for more variance than accounted by one of the original variables in standardized data. #When data is scaled, this is commonly used as a cutoff point for which PCs are retained. (eventhough the 5th value is below 1, but I feel it is close enough to 1 to be considered)

#In the previous assignment, using all the variables crime rate was predicted as 155.4349 (R-squared: 0.8031 ) which was not a good prediction. When using only significant variables, the accuracy increased a bit and the value predicted was 1304.245 (R-squared: 0.7659)within the range of our crime rates(342 to 1993). Yet again, using PCA the predicted value 1388.926 (R-squared: 0.6452) predicted the best value.
